The paper deals with information theoretic aspects of multiuser cognitive radio networks, specifically interference management through message-sharing mechanisms and rate-splitting strategies. This falls under the purview of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of superposition coding and Gel’fand–Pinsker’s binning, which are common techniques in signal processing and machine learning (cs.SY, cs.MM). Finally, the paper focuses on cognitive radio networks, which is a specific area of research in communication and networking (cs.CR).
